"""
mkt-context: Psalms 48-54
Chapters: 48-54 (98 verses)
Run: python3 scripts/zc-context-psalms-48-54.py

Key context decisions:
- Psalm 48: Zion as Zaphon (Ugaritic cosmic mountain of Baal) appropriated for YHWH
- Psalm 49: Wisdom psalm on death/wealth; v15 ransom by God one of OT clearest afterlife hopes
- Psalm 50: Asaph rib (covenant lawsuit); divine-feeding-theory satirized vv10-13
- Psalm 51: Miserere; bara (create, ex nihilo) for clean heart v10; ruach qodshecha Holy Spirit title
- Psalm 52: Doeg the Edomite context (1 Sam 22); tongue-as-razor vs. olive tree contrast
- Psalm 53: Elohist variant of Psalm 14; Paul uses v3 in Rom 3:12
- Psalm 54: Ziphite betrayal context (1 Sam 23:19; 26:1)
"""
import json, pathlib

ROOT = pathlib.Path(__file__).parent.parent

def load_comm(source, book):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / source / f'{book}.json'
    if p.exists():
        return json.loads(p.read_text())
    return {}

def save_comm(source, book, data):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / source / f'{book}.json'
    p.parent.mkdir(parents=True, exist_ok=True)
    p.write_text(json.dumps(data, ensure_ascii=False, indent=None))
    print(f'  wrote {p.relative_to(ROOT)}')

def merge_comm(existing, new_data):
    # INTENT: merge without overwriting any verse already present in existing
    # CHANGE? Do not alter the guard; concurrent agents depend on append-only behavior
    # VERIFY: run twice; second run should report identical byte count for psalms.json
    for ch, verses in new_data.items():
        if ch not in existing:
            existing[ch] = {}
        for v, html in verses.items():
            if v not in existing[ch]:
                existing[ch][v] = html

NEW_DATA = {"48": {"1": "<p><b>Ps 48: Zion Hymn of the Sons of Korah.</b> The Sons of Korah were a Levitical singer guild credited with Pss 42-49, 84-85, 87-88; Korah himself led a failed rebellion against Moses (Num 16), yet his descendants became temple musicians — a remarkable redemptive reversal. Ps 48 is a Zion hymn celebrating Jerusalem as YHWH's cosmic mountain. 'Great is the LORD and greatly to be praised in the city of our God' — the psalm grounds YHWH's praise geographically: his greatness is manifest in and from the holy city.</p>", "2": "<p><b>'Beautiful in elevation, the joy of all the earth, Mount Zion, in the far north (yarkete tzaphon), the city of the great King'</b> — the most theologically charged phrase in the psalm. <i>Yarkete tzaphon</i> (sides/heights of Zaphon) — Zaphon (north/Mount Zaphon) was the sacred mountain of the Canaanite storm-god Baal in Ugaritic texts: the cosmic mountain from which Baal reigned. By claiming Jerusalem as 'Zaphon,' the psalm appropriates Baal's cosmic geography for YHWH — Jerusalem is now the true cosmic mountain, not Baal's northern peak. This is one of the most explicit ANE mythological appropriations in the Psalter.</p>", "3": "<p><b>'Within her citadels God has made himself known as a fortress'</b> — the palace/citadel (<i>armon</i>) of the divine king within the holy city. ANE cities were organized around the palace-temple complex: the king's citadel and the deity's temple were typically adjacent or integrated, expressing the king's rule as mediated through the divine presence. Jerusalem's citadel is YHWH's fortress — the human fortification expresses divine strength.</p>", "4": "<p><b>'For behold, the kings assembled; they came on together'</b> — the 'kings of the earth' gathering against the city of God is a mythological motif that echoes actual historical events (Sennacherib's siege of Jerusalem, 701 BC, when YHWH struck the Assyrian army: 2 Kgs 19:35-36) and anticipates the eschatological gathering of nations against Jerusalem (Ezek 38-39; Zech 12; Rev 19). Whether the specific occasion is historical or prototypical, the pattern is the same: kings gather and fail before YHWH's city.</p>", "5": "<p><b>'As soon as they saw it, they were astounded; they were in panic, they fled away'</b> — the divine panic (<i>bahalu</i>, terror that produces chaos-flight) — YHWH strikes armies with confusion so that they destroy themselves or flee without engaging. This 'holy war' motif appears in Exod 14:24 (YHWH threw the Egyptian army into panic); Josh 10:10 (YHWH threw the Amorite coalition into panic); and 1 Sam 7:10 (YHWH thundered against the Philistines). The terror is the divine weapon, not the military engagement.</p>", "6": "<p><b>'Trembling took hold of them there, anguish as of a woman in labor'</b> — the 'birth pangs' (<i>chil kiyoleda</i>) as the metaphor for overwhelming terror was a standard ANE and biblical comparison for sudden, unstoppable crisis: Isa 13:8; 26:17; Jer 6:24; 22:23; Mic 4:9-10. Labor pains were the most universally understood experience of unavoidable, escalating pain without escape. Armies overtaken by divine panic experienced the same helplessness.</p>", "7": "<p><b>'By the east wind you shattered the ships of Tarshish'</b> — the 'ships of Tarshish' (<i>oniyot tarshish</i>) were the largest long-distance merchant and naval vessels of the ANE, associated with Phoenician trade to the far western Mediterranean (Spain/Sardinia). They were symbols of international power and wealth. YHWH's east wind (<i>ruach qadiym</i>) — the scorching, destructive Levantine wind — shatters even the mightiest vessels. The same wind split the Red Sea in the Exodus tradition (Exod 14:21). Cf. 1 Kgs 22:48; Isa 2:16.</p>", "8": "<p><b>'As we have heard, so have we seen in the city of the LORD of hosts, in the city of our God'</b> — the epistemology of worship: oral tradition ('as we have heard') confirmed by direct experience ('so we have seen'). The community's liturgical memory of YHWH's past saving acts (the Exodus, the conquest) has been verified in present experience. This is the grounding of Israel's worship in actual historical encounter, not merely mythological narrative.</p>", "9": "<p><b>'We have thought on your steadfast love, O God, in the midst of your temple'</b> — <i>diminu chasdechah</i> (we have pondered/meditated your steadfast love) — the temple as the place of theological reflection on <i>chesed</i>. The temple was not only a place of sacrifice but of instruction and meditation: the physical presence in the sanctuary intensified theological reflection. ANE temples were similarly centers of scribal learning and liturgical rehearsal of divine deeds.</p>", "10": "<p><b>'As your name, O God, so your praise reaches to the ends of the earth. Your right hand is filled with righteousness'</b> — the divine name-and-praise universal reach: wherever YHWH's name is known, his praise follows. The 'right hand' (<i>yamin</i>) as the hand of power and justice — the divine right hand performs the saving acts that generate the praise. In ANE iconography, the deity's right hand held the weapon of victory or the scepter of authority.</p>", "11": "<p><b>'Let Mount Zion be glad! Let the daughters of Judah rejoice because of your judgments!'</b> — 'daughters of Judah' (<i>benot yehudah</i>) — the surrounding Judean towns and villages, personified as daughters of the main city. The rejoicing at divine judgments is a covenant celebration: YHWH's acts of justice vindicate the community and expose the wicked. The 'daughters' of a city was a standard ANE idiom for satellite settlements.</p>", "12": "<p><b>'Walk about Zion, go around her, number her towers'</b> — the liturgical circumambulation of Jerusalem. The instruction to walk around and count the towers, strongholds, and citadels of the city was a pedagogical liturgy: the physical inspection of Jerusalem's defenses was a meditation on YHWH's protection. Similar processions appear in other ANE cult contexts (processional routes around temples in Mesopotamia). The counting of towers fixes the community's memory: 'mark well her ramparts.'</p>", "13": "<p><b>'Consider well her ramparts, go through her citadels, that you may tell the next generation'</b> — the intergenerational transmission of the Zion tradition. The physical inspection of Jerusalem (vv12-13) serves a teaching purpose: the next generation (<i>dor acharon</i>) receives the testimony of YHWH's protection through the city's standing. This liturgical pedagogy is analogous to the Passover instruction to children (Exod 12:26-27) and the memorial stones at Gilgal (Josh 4:6-7): physical objects serve as prompts for theological narrative.</p>", "14": "<p><b>'That this is God, our God forever and ever. He will guide us forever'</b> — the psalm closes with the most minimal and complete theological statement: 'This one is God — our God — forever.' The demonstrative <i>zeh</i> (this one) points to the YHWH just described as the fortress of Zion, the shatterer of kings, the guardian of his city. 'He will guide us al-mut' (<i>al muvot</i>, possibly 'beyond death' or 'unto death/forever') — either reading affirms permanent divine guidance.</p>"}, "49": {"1": "<p><b>Ps 49: A Wisdom Psalm on Death and Wealth.</b> One of the most philosophically sophisticated psalms in the Psalter, Ps 49 engages the ANE and universal problem of the apparent prosperity of the wicked and the apparent futility of wisdom in the face of universal death. The Sons of Korah summon 'all peoples' and 'all inhabitants of the world' — this is not a nationalistic psalm but a universal wisdom reflection. 'Hear this, all peoples!' echoes prophetic summons language (Mic 1:2; Isa 34:1).</p>", "2": "<p><b>'Both low and high, rich and poor together'</b> — the wisdom address crosses all social categories. In ANE wisdom literature (Egyptian Instructions, Mesopotamian laments), the problem of death is posed as the great leveler: the Gilgamesh Epic's Siduri explicitly tells Gilgamesh that death awaits both the king and the servant alike. Ps 49 engages this universal problem from a YHWH-centered perspective.</p>", "3": "<p><b>'My mouth will speak wisdom; the meditation of my heart will be understanding'</b> — <i>chokhmot</i> (wisdoms, plural of intensity) and <i>tevunot</i> (understandings, plural) — the plural forms emphasize comprehensive wisdom. <i>Hegeh libbi</i> (meditation of my heart) — the same word for the audible, voiced self-talk of Ps 1:2 and 119:15. The wise teacher processes understanding through voiced reflection before speaking it to the community.</p>", "4": "<p><b>'I will incline my ear to a proverb (mashal); I will open my riddle (chidati) on the lyre'</b> — the teacher introduces a <i>mashal</i> (proverb, wisdom saying, parable) and <i>chidah</i> (riddle, enigma — the same word used for Samson's riddle in Judg 14:12-18 and Ezekiel's riddle in Ezek 17:2). The 'riddle' form invites the audience to engage the problem: why do the wealthy prosper? The lyre accompaniment situates wisdom teaching within the temple music tradition — the riddle is also a song.</p>", "5": "<p><b>'Why should I fear in times of trouble, when the iniquity of those who cheat me surrounds me?'</b> — the psalmist states the problem: surrounded by the iniquity of wealthy oppressors who 'cheat' (<i>aqev</i>, from the root of 'heel/Jacob,' meaning to supplant by underhanded means). The context implies economic exploitation — the kind of legal and commercial manipulation that wealthy patrons could exercise over poorer clients in ANE urban society.</p>", "6": "<p><b>'Those who trust in their wealth and boast of the abundance of their riches'</b> — <i>ha-botchim al-cheilam</i> (those who trust in their wealth) — <i>batach</i> (trust) applied to wealth: the fundamental misdirection of covenant trust vocabulary. YHWH is the proper object of <i>batach</i> (cf. Ps 31:14; 32:10); applying it to wealth is a category error. <i>Cheil</i> (wealth/army/strength) — the same word for military strength and material wealth, suggesting that money functions as a private army for the wealthy.</p>", "7": "<p><b>'Truly no man can ransom another, or give to God the price of his life'</b> — the ransom theme. <i>Pidyon nephesh</i> (ransom of a life) — <i>padah</i> (ransom, pay a redemption price) was a concrete legal and economic practice in the ANE: slaves, prisoners of war, and those under debt-bondage could be ransomed by payment. The argument: for death, no payment is sufficient. This directly engages the ANE attempt to purchase immortality (Gilgamesh's quest for eternal life) — the price of escaping death is categorically beyond human means.</p>", "8": "<p><b>'...for the ransom of his life is costly and can never suffice'</b> — the ransom price exceeds all calculation. ANE societies had developed elaborate schedules for ransom payments (Hammurabi's code specifies ransom amounts for prisoners of war); the point is that no schedule suffices for death's ransom. This verse is the premise of the entire psalm: if wealth cannot ransom the soul, what can?</p>", "9": "<p><b>'...that he should live on forever and never see the pit'</b> — <i>ha-bor</i> (the pit, the grave, Sheol). The wealthy person's ambition — to live forever, to escape death — is categorically impossible by financial means. The pit awaits regardless of wealth. This echoes Qohelet's observation (Eccl 2:14-16) that the wise and the fool share the same death.</p>", "10": "<p><b>'For he sees that even the wise die; the fool and the stupid alike must perish and leave their wealth to others'</b> — the commonality of death across the wisdom-spectrum. Even the wise (<i>chakhamim</i>) die. The fool (<i>kesil</i>) and the stupid (<i>ba'ar</i>, the brutish/ignorant) also die. All leave their accumulated wealth to successors. Qohelet makes the same observation with the same existential distress: the heir may be a fool (Eccl 2:18-21).</p>", "11": "<p><b>'Their graves are their homes forever, their dwelling places to all generations, though they called lands by their own names'</b> — the practice of naming cities, lands, and monuments after oneself as a bid for immortality. Absalom erected a pillar in his name to preserve his memory (2 Sam 18:18). Egyptian pharaohs inscribed their names on every monument. Mesopotamian kings named cities after themselves. Ps 49 punctures this immortality strategy: the land-namers go to the grave regardless.</p>", "12": "<p><b>'Man in his pomp will not remain; he is like the beasts that perish'</b> — <i>adam biqar bal-yalin</i> (man in his splendor/honor does not lodge/remain overnight) — the brevity metaphor: even the most splendid human dignity is as temporary as a night's lodging. 'Like the beasts that perish' — the comparison to animals was the standard ANE symbol for mortality without transcendence: Gilgamesh's companion Enkidu dies as a beast; Gilgamesh himself is told by Siduri that humans are like beasts in their mortality. The psalmist agrees — but will then offer a counter-word in v15.</p>", "13": "<p><b>'This is the path of those who have foolish confidence; after them people approve of their boasts'</b> — <i>kesel</i> (foolish confidence, complacency) — the path of those who trust wealth and self-promotion has admirers: subsequent generations approve the boastful legacy-building. The admiration of the crowd legitimizes what the wisdom tradition condemns. ANE funerary cult (care for the dead, perpetuation of name-memory) was itself a cultural institution that the wealthy could fund and the poor could not.</p>", "14": "<p><b>'Like sheep they are appointed for Sheol; Death shall be their shepherd, and the upright shall rule over them in the morning'</b> — 'Death as shepherd' (<i>mavet yiream</i>) — a grotesque inversion of the divine shepherd image (Ps 23). Death shepherds the wealthy into Sheol as a flock is driven into a pen. 'The upright shall rule over them in the morning' — the eschatological reversal: those who were exploited in life will have dominion over their exploiters in the morning (either of resurrection or of divine judgment). The 'morning' as the time of divine intervention recurs in Ps 46:5 and 143:8.</p>", "15": "<p><b>'But God will ransom my soul from the power of Sheol, for he will receive me'</b> — the pivotal counter-word. <i>Ach</i> (but/however) — the adversative marks the psalm's theological turn. <i>Padah</i> (ransom) — the same ransom word from vv7-8, where it was declared impossible: no human can ransom another. But God can. <i>Ki yiqacheni</i> (for he will receive/take me) — the same verb used of Enoch's translation: 'Enoch walked with God and was no more, for God took him' (<i>laqach</i>, Gen 5:24). This is one of the most explicit hope-of-resurrection statements in the Psalter before Daniel 12.</p>", "16": "<p><b>'Be not afraid when a man becomes rich, when the glory of his house increases'</b> — the pastoral application of the theological argument: the prosperity of the wicked should not produce fear or envy. The instruction addresses the existential anxiety of those economically vulnerable to the wealthy oppressor. The wisdom teacher turns philosophical reflection into practical pastoral guidance for those tempted to abandon covenant fidelity for material advantage.</p>", "17": "<p><b>'For when he dies he will carry nothing away; his glory will not go down after him'</b> — the impossibility of posthumous wealth-retention was a commonplace in ANE wisdom. Despite elaborate Egyptian funerary provision (grave goods, shabtis, food for the dead), the practical reality was that no wealth accompanied the dead person into the afterlife. The futility of accumulation without transcendence is Qohelet's obsessive theme (Eccl 5:15: 'as he came from his mother's womb, so he will return').</p>", "18": "<p><b>'For though, while he lives, he counts himself blessed — and though you get praise when you do well for yourself'</b> — the social approval given to the successful wealthy. 'Counting himself blessed' (<i>yevorekh nephsho</i>) — self-congratulation. 'When you do well for yourself' (<i>ki-tetiv lecha</i>) — the social pressure to define success as personal prosperity. The community that applauds wealth accumulation validates the system the psalm critiques.</p>", "19": "<p><b>'His soul will go to the generation of his fathers, who will never again see light'</b> — the underworld as the community of the ancestors: the dead join the prior generations in Sheol. The phrase 'will never again see light' — light as the characteristic of life and divine presence (Ps 36:9; 56:13); Sheol is the land without light (Job 10:21-22). The wealthy person's soul enters the darkness of the ancestral underworld, regardless of the house's visible glory.</p>", "20": "<p><b>'Man in his pomp yet without understanding is like the beasts that perish'</b> — the psalm closes with the refrain from v12, with a significant modification: 'without understanding' (<i>velo yavin</i> replaces <i>bal-yalin</i>, 'will not remain'). The final word is not about mortality per se but about the failure to understand the psalm's own wisdom. The beast-mortality is the fate of those who accumulate without comprehension of the psalm's teaching. Those who hear and understand the riddle (v4) are those who can respond to v15's hope.</p>"}, "50": {"1": "<p><b>Ps 50: Asaph's Covenant Lawsuit (Rib) Psalm.</b> The Asaph psalms (50, 73-83) are associated with the Asaphite Levitical singer guild, tracing their lineage to Asaph, David's chief musician (1 Chr 6:39; 16:5; 25:1-2). Ps 50 opens with the triple divine name: <i>El Elohim YHWH</i> (the Mighty One, God, the LORD) — echoing Josh 22:22's covenantal formula and possibly the liturgical summons of Ps 82. This is a <i>rib</i> (covenant lawsuit) psalm: YHWH acts as plaintiff, judge, and divine prosecutor summoning his covenant people to account.</p>", "2": "<p><b>'Out of Zion, the perfection of beauty, God shines forth'</b> — <i>mikallal yophi</i> (the perfection/completeness of beauty) — Zion as the supremely beautiful place. 'God shines forth' (<i>hophia</i>) — the theophanic verb: YHWH's self-manifestation from the holy city is like the sun breaking out. The cosmic court is convened from the most beautiful and sacred place on earth.</p>", "3": "<p><b>'Our God comes; he does not keep silence; before him is a devouring fire, around him a mighty tempest'</b> — the storm-theophany of the divine court: fire and storm accompany the divine judge. This is the Sinai theophany pattern (Exod 19:18; Deut 4:11-12; 5:23-25) applied to the covenant lawsuit: the same God who gave the law now comes to prosecute its violation. ANE divine court scenes also featured storm theophany as the marker of divine presence and authority (the Baal Cycle's storm-god court).</p>", "4": "<p><b>'He calls to the heavens above and to the earth, that he may judge his people'</b> — heaven and earth as the witnesses to the covenant lawsuit. The Deuteronomic covenant formula explicitly called heaven and earth as witnesses to the covenant (Deut 4:26; 30:19; 31:28; Isa 1:2). The <i>rib</i> (covenant lawsuit) genre in the prophets (Mic 6:1-8; Isa 1:2-20; Jer 2:4-13) always summons these witnesses. Their presence in the court validates the proceedings.</p>", "5": "<p><b>'Gather to me my faithful ones, who made a covenant with me by sacrifice'</b> — <i>chasidai</i> (my faithful/covenant-loyal ones) — the covenant-loyal community is summoned as the defendant. 'Who made a covenant with me by sacrifice' (<i>korethe beriti alei zevach</i>) — the sacrifice-ratified covenant at Sinai (Exod 24:5-8: Moses threw the blood of sacrifices on the people, ratifying the covenant). The sacrifice-covenant connection is the specific legal basis for the lawsuit: they entered the covenant through sacrifice, now they misuse sacrifice.</p>", "6": "<p><b>'The heavens declare his righteousness, for God himself is judge'</b> — the created witnesses declare the divine righteousness of the proceedings: the lawsuit is cosmically valid. <i>Ki-Elohim shofet hu</i> (for God himself is judge) — the divine self-identification as judge within the cosmic court. The same heavens that were called as witnesses (v4) now declare the judge's righteousness: the cosmos testifies to YHWH's legal competence and moral authority.</p>", "7": "<p><b>'Hear, O my people, and I will speak; O Israel, I will testify against you. I am God, your God'</b> — the divine self-identification at the opening of the indictment: <i>Elohim Eloheycha anochi</i> (I am God, your God) — the Decalogue formula (Exod 20:2: 'I am the LORD your God who brought you out of Egypt'). The lawsuit proceeds on the basis of prior covenant relationship. YHWH is not an outside critic but the covenant partner bringing charges against his own people.</p>", "8": "<p><b>'Not for your sacrifices do I rebuke you; your burnt offerings are continually before me'</b> — the startling opening of the indictment: the charge is not failure to offer sacrifices. The sacrifices are happening; the problem is the understanding of what sacrifice does. This is the prophetic critique of mechanical sacrifice (Isa 1:11-15; Jer 7:21-23; Amos 5:21-24; Mic 6:6-8): external religious practice unconnected to covenant faithfulness is rejected, not the institution of sacrifice itself.</p>", "9": "<p><b>'I will not accept a bull from your house or goats from your folds'</b> — the divine rejection of animal sacrifice offered with false understanding. The contrast is not between sacrifice and non-sacrifice but between sacrifice as magical transaction and sacrifice as covenant expression. ANE sacrifice operated on the logic of feeding the gods (divine food theory), which Ps 50 directly attacks in vv12-13. Israelite sacrifice should operate on the logic of covenant re-affirmation.</p>", "10": "<p><b>'For every beast of the forest is mine, the cattle on a thousand hills'</b> — the divine ownership argument: YHWH already owns all the animals. The ANE divine-feeding theory assumed gods needed human provision; Ps 50 exposes the logical absurdity — the creator-God who owns every animal on earth does not need Israel's specific bulls and goats as food supply. This is a direct satire of ANE temple economies where temple servants 'fed' the divine statue three meals daily.</p>", "11": "<p><b>'I know all the birds of the hills, and all that moves in the field is mine'</b> — the comprehensive divine inventory: YHWH knows and owns every living thing. The enumeration of divine ownership (vv10-12) accumulates to make the point unanswerable: what could Israel offer that YHWH does not already possess?</p>", "12": "<p><b>'If I were hungry, I would not tell you, for the world and its fullness are mine'</b> — the ironic conditional: divine hunger is hypothetical and, if actual, would not be communicated to humans, because the creator-God owns the entire world's food supply. 'The world and its fullness' (<i>tevel umelo'ah</i>) — cf. Ps 24:1. The argument is complete: YHWH cannot need Israel's sacrifices as food. The Mesopotamian creation texts (Atrahasis) explained that the gods created humans specifically to labor and provide the divine food supply — Ps 50 directly refutes this theology.</p>", "13": "<p><b>'Do I eat the flesh of bulls or drink the blood of goats?'</b> — the rhetorical question that exposes the ANE divine-feeding assumption. 'Do I eat... do I drink?' — categorically no. This verse explicitly refutes the theology of divine sustenance that underlay Mesopotamian and Canaanite temple cult. The Canaanite texts from Ugarit depict Baal's feast; Mesopotamian texts describe the divine meal. Ps 50 says: YHWH is not that kind of god.</p>", "14": "<p><b>'Offer to God a sacrifice of thanksgiving, and perform your vows to the Most High'</b> — the positive instruction: <i>zevach todah</i> (sacrifice of thanksgiving) — the thanksgiving offering (<i>todah</i>) was a specific type of peace offering (Lev 7:12-15) offered by a person who had been rescued from distress. It was accompanied by the public recitation of the rescue narrative — the lament psalm resolved into thanksgiving. This is what YHWH wants: the acknowledgment of his saving acts through genuine praise.</p>", "15": "<p><b>'And call upon me in the day of trouble; I will deliver you, and you shall glorify me'</b> — the covenant transaction re-framed: not sacrifice-for-divine-favor but prayer-for-deliverance-then-thanksgiving. <i>Qera'eni beyom tzarah</i> (call on me in the day of trouble) — the prayer-and-rescue dynamic is the authentic core of covenant relationship. The mechanical sacrifice bypasses this relational dynamic; genuine prayer and honest acknowledgment of rescue constitute true worship.</p>", "16": "<p><b>'But to the wicked God says: What right have you to recite my statutes or take my covenant on your lips?'</b> — the second charge of the lawsuit: the wicked within the covenant community use the correct religious language while living contrary to its content. 'Recite my statutes' (<i>sippercha chuqqai</i>) and 'take my covenant on your lips' (<i>nasa beriti alei picha</i>) — they speak the covenant language without covenant practice. This is the Pharisee critique later made explicit in the NT: correct formulas without the transformation of life.</p>", "17": "<p><b>'For you hate discipline, and you cast my words behind you'</b> — <i>hatah musar</i> (you hate correction/discipline) — <i>musar</i> (discipline, instruction, the correction-pain that produces wisdom) is the core of the wisdom tradition (Prov 1:7; 3:11-12). Hating correction while claiming Torah is the quintessential hypocrisy: taking the benefits of the covenant (identity, protection) while rejecting its demands (discipline, transformation).</p>", "18": "<p><b>'If you see a thief, you are pleased with him, and you keep company with adulterers'</b> — the list of covenant violations: theft and adultery are two of the Ten Commandments (Exod 20:14-15). Association with violators constitutes complicity. In the ANE legal framework, witness to a crime without reporting it made the bystander complicit. The covenant community's casual association with lawbreakers indicates their indifference to the covenant law they publicly profess.</p>", "19": "<p><b>'You give your mouth free rein for evil, and your tongue frames deceit'</b> — the mouth/tongue as the instrument of sin: false witness, malicious speech, slander. The covenant's ninth commandment (false witness, Exod 20:16) and the wisdom tradition's heavy emphasis on speech (Prov 10:19; 18:21; James 3) converge here. The community that 'takes the covenant on their lips' (v16) uses those same lips for deceit.</p>", "20": "<p><b>'You sit and speak against your brother; you slander your own mother's son'</b> — slander of family members ('your own mother's son' — the intimate kin who shares the same mother). Family slander was a particularly serious covenant violation: honor within the family unit was the foundation of social order. 'Sit and speak' — the casual, settled nature of the slander: not explosive anger but habitual character assassination.</p>", "21": "<p><b>'These things you have done, and I have been silent; you thought that I was one like yourself. But now I rebuke you and lay the charge before you'</b> — the divine silence misread as divine approval. 'You thought I was one like yourself' (<i>hayyiti chamocha</i>) — the most disturbing indictment: the covenant community has made YHWH in their own image, assuming that because he has not acted, he condones. ANE deities were understood through the lens of human patrons who could be placated, delayed, or ignored. YHWH here asserts his moral difference from human models.</p>", "22": "<p><b>'Mark this, then, you who forget God, lest I tear you apart, and there be none to deliver!'</b> — the divine warning with the most severe consequence: YHWH himself as the one who 'tears apart' (<i>tiroph</i>, the lion-word used for violent predators). 'None to deliver' — all the human and divine protections fail when YHWH becomes the adversary. The covenant's curse section in Deut 28 warned that YHWH himself would become the enemy of covenant-breakers.</p>", "23": "<p><b>'The one who offers thanksgiving as his sacrifice glorifies me; to one who orders his way rightly I will show the salvation of God'</b> — the psalm's closing positive instruction summarizes its entire argument: genuine thanksgiving (<i>todah</i>) glorifies God; right conduct (<i>sam derekh</i>, ordering the way) receives divine salvation. The two elements — authentic worship and covenant-aligned living — are inseparable. Neither sacrifice without life nor life without sacrifice: the covenant is a relational whole.</p>"}, "51": {"1": "<p><b>Ps 51: The Miserere — The Penitential Psalm par excellence.</b> The superscription links the psalm to 2 Sam 11-12: David's sin with Bathsheba (adultery, complicity in Uriah's death) and Nathan's confrontation ('you are the man'). The historical occasion grounds the psalm's universality: if David — the man after God's own heart, the author of the Psalter — requires this depth of confession, so does every person. The psalm became the primary penitential text of both Jewish liturgy (morning prayers) and Christian practice (Ash Wednesday, the Daily Office, pre-Communion confession).</p><p><b>'Have mercy on me, O God, according to your steadfast love'</b> — <i>chonneni El kechasdecha</i> — the petition is grounded in divine character, not in any claim the petitioner can make. <i>Chesed</i> (steadfast/covenant love) and <i>rachame</i> (compassion/womb-love, plural) are the two divine attributes invoked. The plural 'according to the abundance of your compassion' is a quantity modifier: the sin is vast; the compassion must be correspondingly vast.</p>", "2": "<p><b>'Wash me thoroughly from my iniquity, and cleanse me from my sin'</b> — two purification metaphors: <i>kabbes</i> (wash thoroughly, the laundry/fulling word — beating and scrubbing cloth clean) and <i>tahar</i> (make ritually pure, the Levitical cleanness term). The first is intense domestic cleaning; the second is ritual/covenantal restoration. Both are needed: the sin is simultaneously a moral stain requiring thorough removal and a ritual impurity requiring Levitical purification procedures. Cf. Lev 14 (purification of skin disease) and Num 19 (purification from corpse contamination).</p>", "3": "<p><b>'For I know my transgressions, and my sin is ever before me'</b> — the confession of full self-knowledge. The three sin-words in vv1-3: <i>pesha</i> (willful rebellion/breach of covenant), <i>avon</i> (iniquity/moral crookedness), <i>chata</i> (sin, missing the mark). All three appear again in v2, making Ps 51 a comprehensive survey of Israel's sin-vocabulary. 'Ever before me' — the inability to escape the awareness of the sin: it is constantly visible in the conscience.</p>", "4": "<p><b>'Against you, you only, have I sinned and done what is evil in your sight'</b> — <i>lecha levadecha chatati</i> (against you, you alone, have I sinned). This verse has generated sustained theological debate: David sinned against Bathsheba and Uriah, so how 'only' against God? The answer is covenantal: all sin is ultimately a breach of the covenant relationship with YHWH, who is the source of all moral obligation. 'So that you are justified in your words and blameless in your judgment' — YHWH's verdict is accepted before it is pronounced. Paul cites this in Rom 3:4 to establish YHWH's judicial rectitude.</p>", "5": "<p><b>'Behold, I was brought forth in iniquity, and in sin did my mother conceive me'</b> — <i>hen beaven cholalti</i> (behold, in iniquity I was formed/writhed). This verse has been foundational in the Western church's theology of original sin (Augustine, the Reformers). The grammatical subject is the psalmist, not the mother: it is not a claim about maternal sin during conception but about the structural moral condition of the human person from the earliest moment of existence. Comparison: Job 14:4 ('who can bring clean from unclean?'); Gen 6:5 ('every intention of the thoughts of his heart was only evil continually'). The verse does not celebrate this condition but confesses it as the ground for the radical, divine intervention the psalm requests.</p>", "6": "<p><b>'Behold, you delight in truth in the inward being, and you teach me wisdom in the secret heart'</b> — <i>emet batuchot</i> (truth in the inner parts) — YHWH desires truth in the most hidden interior, not external compliance. The 'secret heart' (<i>satom</i>, the concealed/hidden place) is where wisdom must be taught. ANE temple religion focused on visible acts of sacrifice and ritual; the Psalter (especially the penitential psalms) insists that YHWH's real demand is interior transformation. This is the ground for the 'create in me a clean heart' petition of v10.</p>", "7": "<p><b>'Purge me with hyssop, and I shall be clean; wash me, and I shall be whiter than snow'</b> — <i>techateni</i> (purge me with hyssop) — <i>hyssop</i> (<i>ezov</i>) was the small, bushy plant used to apply the purification blood and water in Levitical rituals: the purification of skin disease (Lev 14:4-7), the red heifer purification from corpse contamination (Num 19:18). Jesus is offered wine on hyssop at the cross (John 19:29). 'Whiter than snow' — snow as the superlative of whiteness and purity, used in Isa 1:18 for the transformation of scarlet sins to white.</p>", "8": "<p><b>'Let me hear joy and gladness; let the bones that you have broken rejoice'</b> — 'the bones you have broken' — the physical experience of divine judgment as broken bones: the intensity of the guilt as a skeletal fracturing. The request to 'hear joy and gladness' is a request that the hearing-organs, previously afflicted by the sound of divine judgment, now receive the sound of rescue. ANE lament texts similarly describe illness as the crushing of bones and the healing as the restoration of normal function.</p>", "9": "<p><b>'Hide your face from my sins, and blot out all my iniquities'</b> — the divine face-hiding request: in v7-9 the psalmist asks for YHWH not to see the sin. <i>Macheh</i> (blot out, erase from a record) — the cancellation of a written debt or legal record. ANE contracts were written on clay tablets; debt cancellation was literally the erasure of the tablet. YHWH's ledger of sins is requested to be erased.</p>", "10": "<p><b>'Create in me a clean heart, O God, and renew a right spirit within me'</b> — <i>bara li lev tahor</i> (create for me a clean heart). <i>Bara</i> (create) is the Genesis 1 term, used exclusively of divine action, the creation from nothing or the transformation of something categorically new. The request is for a moral creation event: YHWH must create ex nihilo a clean heart, because the existing heart is not renewable by repair — it needs to be made new. This is the most theologically radical verse of the psalm and anticipates the new covenant promise of Jer 31:31-34 and Ezek 36:26 ('I will give you a new heart').</p>", "11": "<p><b>'Cast me not away from your presence, and take not your Holy Spirit from me'</b> — <i>ruach qodshecha</i> (your Holy Spirit) — one of only three occurrences of 'Holy Spirit' in the OT (Isa 63:10-11). In the context of 2 Sam 16:14 (the Spirit departed from Saul), David's prayer reflects the awareness that YHWH's Spirit can be withdrawn from those who fall from covenant faithfulness. The 'presence' (<i>panecha</i>) and the 'Holy Spirit' are parallel: the Spirit is the mode of divine presence. This verse became central to pneumatological discussion in the NT era.</p>", "12": "<p><b>'Restore to me the joy of your salvation, and uphold me with a willing spirit'</b> — <i>ruach nedivah</i> (a willing/noble/generous spirit) — <i>nadiv</i> (willing, the freewill-offering word from <i>nadav</i>) — the spirit characterized by voluntary, generous responsiveness rather than coerced compliance. The renewed spirit is freely willing, not mechanically obedient. This is the Jeremiah/Ezekiel new covenant anthropology: the law written on the heart produces willing obedience, not legal compulsion.</p>", "13": "<p><b>'Then I will teach transgressors your ways, and sinners will return to you'</b> — the restored sinner becomes the teacher of other sinners. The logic of testimony: personal experience of divine forgiveness becomes the most persuasive evidence for others. The psalm that began with individual confession (v3) now projects communal impact: the psalmist's restored relationship will generate the conversion of others. This is the same dynamic as John 4 (the Samaritan woman's testimony) and Ps 22:22-31 (the individual rescue becomes communal praise).</p>", "14": "<p><b>'Deliver me from bloodguiltiness, O God, O God of my salvation, and my tongue will sing aloud of your righteousness'</b> — <i>damim</i> (bloodguilt, bloods plural) — the specific sin of Uriah's death. The plural 'bloods' in Hebrew law referred to the guilt of multiple blood-related deaths, including not only the killer but those who arranged or enabled the killing. David arranged Uriah's death through Joab; the multiple layers of guilt are captured in the plural. 'My tongue will sing' — praise is the result of forgiveness, not the condition for it.</p>", "15": "<p><b>'O Lord, open my lips, and my mouth will declare your praise'</b> — the lips must be divinely opened for praise: the guilty mouth cannot offer praise on its own initiative. This petition became the opening prayer of the Daily Office in Christian liturgy: 'O Lord, open my lips, and my mouth shall declare your praise' (the Versicle before morning prayer). The guilt of the lips (they participated in the conspiracy of silence, vv3-5) must be released by divine action before they can speak praise.</p>", "16": "<p><b>'For you will not delight in sacrifice, or I would give it; you will not be pleased with a burnt offering'</b> — the Asaph/Ps 50 theme within Ps 51: sacrifice is not what YHWH wants most. This verse has a precise historical setting: after the murder of Uriah, David could offer no sacrifice to undo the sin — no animal payment could cover premeditated murder. The psalm therefore reaches for something deeper than the sacrificial system: the interior transformation of vv10-12 is what no temple sacrifice can accomplish.</p>", "17": "<p><b>'The sacrifices of God are a broken spirit; a broken and contrite heart, O God, you will not despise'</b> — <i>zivche Elohim ruach nishbarah</i> (the sacrifices of God are a broken spirit) — the paradox: the sacrifice that YHWH actually desires is the crushed, humbled person. <i>Nishbarah</i> (broken, shattered) + <i>nidkeh</i> (crushed, contrite) — two words for the complete demolition of self-sufficiency. YHWH does not despise this offering. The broken person offering the broken spirit is precisely what the whole sacrificial system was designed to express and effect — now articulated in its purest, interiorized form.</p>", "18": "<p><b>'Do good to Zion in your good pleasure; build up the walls of Jerusalem'</b> — vv18-19 are widely regarded as a later addition, possibly exilic or post-exilic, redirecting the individual penitential psalm toward communal restoration. 'Build up the walls of Jerusalem' implies that the walls are broken — consistent with the post-586 BC context. The individual's confession is extended to national confession and restoration. This addition transforms the psalm into the prayer of the exile community: just as David needed forgiveness and restoration, so does exiled Israel.</p>", "19": "<p><b>'Then you will delight in right sacrifices, in burnt offerings and whole burnt offerings; then bulls will be offered on your altar'</b> — the eschatological restoration of sacrifice after communal renewal. The polemic of vv16-17 (against hollow sacrifice) is not a permanent abolition of sacrifice but a diagnosis of current inauthenticity: when the interior condition is right (v17, the broken and contrite heart), the exterior sacrifices become genuine expressions of that condition. Bulls on the restored altar express the restored community's authentic covenant worship.</p>"}, "52": {"1": "<p><b>Ps 52: Against the Boastful Powerful (Doeg the Edomite).</b> The superscription links the psalm to 1 Sam 22:9-22: Doeg the Edomite, Saul's chief herdsman, witnessed David's visit to Ahimelech the priest at Nob. He reported this to Saul (1 Sam 22:9-10), then carried out Saul's order to massacre 85 priests at Nob and their families — a slaughter that Saul's own soldiers refused to execute (1 Sam 22:17-18). Doeg represents the court official whose information and power-loyalty leads to the destruction of the innocent. 'Why do you boast of evil, O mighty man?' — <i>gibbor</i> (mighty man, hero — the military/social elite title) addresses the powerful who misuse their position.</p>", "2": "<p><b>'Your tongue plots destruction, like a sharp razor, you worker of deceit'</b> — the tongue as razor: the most dangerous weapon is not a sword but speech in the ear of power. Doeg's 'tongue' — his report to Saul — was the instrument that destroyed the priests. The razor metaphor appears in Isa 7:20 (YHWH's judgment as a razor) and here as an image of the devastating precision of malicious speech. <i>Remiyyah</i> (deceit) — slackness/treachery in the manner of a slipping bow-string (Hos 7:16).</p>", "3": "<p><b>'You love evil more than good, and lying more than speaking what is right'</b> — the character diagnosis: the boastful powerful person is not accidentally evil but constitutively oriented toward evil over good, falsehood over truth. This is the fool/wicked person of Proverbs: not ignorant but perversely choosing the wrong direction. ANE court culture rewarded those who told powerful people what they wanted to hear (<i>yes-men</i>); Doeg's information served Saul's paranoia.</p>", "4": "<p><b>'You love all words that devour, O deceitful tongue'</b> — <i>kol-divvrei vala</i> (all devouring words) — speech as consumption: words that eat up the innocent. The devouring-speech metaphor appears in wisdom literature (Prov 12:6; Eccl 10:12) and prophets (Jer 5:14). Doeg's words devoured 85 priestly lives.</p>", "5": "<p><b>'But God will break you down forever; he will snatch and tear you from your tent; he will uproot you from the land of the living'</b> — the divine counter-action: three destruction verbs: <i>nitatzecha</i> (break down/demolish), <i>yachtecha</i> (snatch up), <i>shereshecha</i> (uproot). The tent (<i>ohel</i>) as the household/family unit: total destruction of the person, family, and legacy. 'Land of the living' (<i>eretz chayyim</i>) — life as the covenant blessing; being uprooted from the land of the living is premature, covenant-curse death.</p>", "6": "<p><b>'The righteous shall see and fear, and shall laugh at him, saying</b> — the community's response to divine judgment on the powerful: first fear (<i>yira'u</i> — reverential awe at divine action) then laughter (<i>yischaq</i>) — not mockery for its own sake but the laughter of vindication, the release of tension when the threatening power is finally broken. This is the laughter of Ps 2:4 (YHWH laughing at the plotting nations): the reversal of power is laughable in retrospect.</p>", "7": "<p><b>'See the man who would not make God his refuge, but trusted in the abundance of his riches and sought refuge in his own destruction'</b> — the theological epitaph: he 'did not make God his refuge (<i>maoz</i>)' but trusted in riches (<i>oshro</i>). The <i>maoz</i> (fortress/refuge) vocabulary is the Psalter's word for the proper object of trust; Doeg's fortress was his position in Saul's court and the intelligence that gave him power over others. His 'destruction' (<i>hauto</i>) was his ruin: he sought refuge in the very thing that destroyed him.</p>", "8": "<p><b>'But I am like a green olive tree in the house of God. I trust in the steadfast love of God forever and ever'</b> — the contrast of Doeg's uprooting (v5) with the psalmist's olive tree. The olive tree was one of the most valuable and long-lived trees of the ANE: olive trees can live for thousands of years (ancient trees still standing in Gethsemane), produce valuable oil for decades, and were a primary symbol of prosperity and blessing (Ps 128:3; Jer 11:16). To be 'like a green olive tree in the house of God' is to be deeply rooted, enduringly productive, and continuously blessed.</p>", "9": "<p><b>'I will thank you forever, because you have done it. I will wait for your name, for it is good, in the presence of the godly'</b> — the vow of thanksgiving: <i>odecha leolam</i> (I will thank you forever). 'Because you have done it' (<i>ki-asita</i>) — the vague demonstrative anticipates the divine action of rescue and vindication. 'In the presence of the godly' (<i>chasidecha</i>, your faithful ones) — the public testimony before the covenant community. The private experience of divine faithfulness becomes communal testimony.</p>"}, "53": {"1": "<p><b>Ps 53: The Elohist's Psalm 14.</b> Ps 53 is nearly identical to Ps 14 but belongs to the 'Elohist Psalter' (Pss 42-83), which systematically uses <i>Elohim</i> where the rest of the Psalter uses <i>YHWH</i>. The reason for the Elohist Psalter is debated: possibly a liturgical variant for contexts where the divine name was not spoken, or from a different editorial tradition. The superscription adds 'On Mahalath' — a musical term of uncertain meaning (possibly the name of a tune, a type of instrument, or 'for sickness'). 'A Maskil of David' — the instructional psalm label.</p><p><b>'The fool has said in his heart, There is no God'</b> — <i>nabal</i> (fool) is the moral fool of wisdom literature: not the intellectually challenged but the one who is morally obtuse, practically ungodly. <i>Nabal</i> famously appears in 1 Sam 25 (the man whose name was Nabal, meaning 'fool'); the word designates the person who acts without reference to God's moral order. 'In his heart' — not a public atheistic declaration but a private, practical god-lessness: acting as if YHWH does not observe or judge.</p>", "2": "<p><b>'God looks down from heaven on the children of man, to see if there are any who understand, who seek after God'</b> — the divine survey: YHWH looks for genuine seekers (<i>dorshei Elohim</i>, those who pursue God) and finds none. The divine searching is a judgment: the creator who made humans to seek him finds universal practical atheism. This is the same divine survey as in Gen 18:21 (YHWH investigating Sodom) — the judge descending to examine the evidence.</p>", "3": "<p><b>'They have all fallen away; together they have become corrupt; there is none who does good, not even one'</b> — <i>hakol sar yachdav ne'elahu</i> (all have turned aside; together they have become corrupt/sour) — the universal apostasy. Paul cites v3 (and Ps 14:3) in Rom 3:12 as part of his catena of OT texts establishing universal human sinfulness (Rom 3:10-18). The 'not even one' (<i>ein gam echad</i>) emphasizes totality: no exception.</p>", "4": "<p><b>'Have those who work evil no knowledge, who eat up my people as they eat bread and do not call upon God?'</b> — 'eating my people like bread' — the exploitation metaphor of predatory consumption: the powerful feed on the poor as casually as eating daily bread. Mic 3:3 uses similar language ('who eat the flesh of my people'). ANE economic systems allowed the wealthy to consume the resources of the poor through debt, foreclosure, and labor exploitation. The exploiters 'do not call upon God' — <i>batach</i> vocabulary is absent: they have no covenant relationship that could moderate their predation.</p>", "5": "<p><b>'There they are, in great terror, where there is no terror! For God scatters the bones of him who encamps against you; you put them to shame, for God has rejected them'</b> — the divine reversal: the oppressors experience 'great terror' in a place 'where there is no terror' — the divine panic (cf. Ps 48:5) strikes where no objective threat exists. 'God scatters the bones' — the most radical military victory image: not just defeat but the total disintegration of the enemy's physical remains, which were left unburied (the greatest ANE disgrace). The variant from Ps 14 here is notable: Ps 14 reads differently in v5, suggesting this variant has a different historical or liturgical application.</p>", "6": "<p><b>'Oh, that salvation for Israel would come out of Zion! When God restores the fortunes of his people, let Jacob rejoice, let Israel be glad'</b> — the eschatological longing: the universal diagnosis of human sinfulness (vv1-4) ends not in despair but in prayer for divine salvation. 'Restores the fortunes' (<i>shivit shevut</i>) — the restoration-from-exile formula: the same phrase used in Jer 29:14; Ezek 39:25; Amos 9:14 for the eschatological return from captivity. The psalm's cry for Israel's salvation from within the context of universal human failure is the precise prayer that the NT announces has been answered in Christ.</p>"}, "54": {"1": "<p><b>Ps 54: Davidic Lament — The Ziphite Betrayal.</b> The superscription links to two occasions when the Ziphites (Judahites from Ziph in the Judean desert) informed Saul of David's whereabouts: 1 Sam 23:19 and 26:1. The betrayal by fellow-Judeans — not Philistines or Canaanites — was particularly bitter: the informers were from David's own tribe. 'Save me, O God, by your name' — <i>bemishpecha</i> (by your name) — the divine name as the active agency of rescue. The name YHWH is not merely a label but the embodiment of divine character and power; invoking the name is invoking the full weight of YHWH's covenant identity.</p>", "2": "<p><b>'Hear my prayer, O God; give ear to the words of my mouth'</b> — the double petition for divine auditory attention. <i>Tefillati</i> (my prayer) + <i>imrei fi</i> (words of my mouth) — both the structured prayer and the specific verbal content are presented. The sanctuary context: petitions were offered in the direction of the Jerusalem temple, where YHWH's presence was localized (1 Kgs 8:28-30).</p>", "3": "<p><b>'For strangers have risen against me; ruthless men seek my life; they do not set God before them'</b> — <i>zarim</i> (strangers/insolent ones — the term is ambiguous; some manuscripts read <i>zedim</i>, the arrogant/presumptuous). The Ziphite informers were technically Israelites but are called 'strangers' because their betrayal placed them outside the covenant community of loyalty. 'They do not set God before them' — the practical atheism formula (cf. Ps 53:1): not formal unbelief but behavior that ignores YHWH's moral order.</p>", "4": "<p><b>'Behold, God is my helper; the Lord is the upholder of my life'</b> — the pivot from petition to confidence: <i>hinneh Elohim ozer li</i> (behold, God is my helper). <i>Ezer</i> (helper — the Gen 2:18 word, used of YHWH as Israel's helper: Exod 18:4; Deut 33:29). 'The upholder of my life' (<i>somech naphshi</i>) — <i>samach</i> (to lean on, support) is the same word for laying hands on the sacrifice (Lev 1:4): YHWH bears the weight of the psalmist's life as the offerer bears on the sacrifice.</p>", "5": "<p><b>'He will return the evil to my enemies; in your faithfulness put an end to them'</b> — the lex talionis petition: <i>yashuv hara le-shorerai</i> (return the evil upon my foes). The divine faithfulness (<i>emet</i>, truth/reliability) is invoked as the mechanism of justice: the same reliable character that makes YHWH's promises trustworthy also makes his judgments trustworthy. The prayer for enemy destruction is grounded not in vindictiveness but in covenant justice.</p>", "6": "<p><b>'With a freewill offering I will sacrifice to you; I will give thanks to your name, O LORD, for it is good'</b> — <i>nedavah</i> (freewill offering, voluntary sacrifice — from <i>nadav</i>, to volunteer willingly). The freewill offering was not commanded by schedule but offered by voluntary impulse of gratitude, usually in response to rescue or blessing. The vow is proleptic: made before the rescue in confident anticipation. <i>Ki tov</i> (for it is good) — the goodness of the divine name (= divine character) is the ground of thanksgiving.</p>", "7": "<p><b>'For he has delivered me from every trouble, and my eye has looked in triumph on my enemies'</b> — the past-tense assurance of rescue: <i>ki mikol-tzarah hitzilani</i> (for from every trouble he has delivered me) — perfect tense expressing certainty. 'My eye has looked in triumph on my enemies' (<i>uveoyvai reatah eini</i>) — the idiom of the eye seeing what it desired: the vindication of the psalmist is visible. The psalm closes in the register of completed confidence despite the ongoing external threat, the characteristic move of lament psalmody.</p>"}}

if __name__ == '__main__':
    book = 'psalms'
    source = 'mkt-context'
    existing = load_comm(source, book)
    merge_comm(existing, NEW_DATA)
    save_comm(source, book, existing)
    for ch, vv in NEW_DATA.items():
        saved = existing.get(ch, {})
        missing = [v for v in vv if v not in saved]
        print(f'  ch {ch}: {len(vv)} entries, {len(missing)} missing after merge')
